# Comment Standards

## Comment Syntax

Use **only** `(* *)` comment syntax. Never use `//` single-line comments.

| Type | Syntax | Example |
|------|--------|---------|
| Single-line | `(* text *)` | `(* Enable the controller *)` |
| Multi-line | `(* text ... text *)` | `(* Signal must stay TRUE for tActivate before Q goes TRUE. Signal must stay FALSE for tDeactivate before Q goes FALSE. *)` |
| Nested | `(* outer (* inner *) *)` | `(* a := fbTest.out; (* disabled *) b := b + 1; *)` |

TwinCAT supports nested `(* *)` comments — inner `(* *)` pairs are allowed inside outer ones. This is useful for commenting out code blocks that already contain comments.

## FB / FUNCTION Header

One-line `(* *)` purpose comment before `FUNCTION_BLOCK` / `FUNCTION`. Multi-line for complex FBs (max 3 lines). This comment appears as tooltip in TwinCAT XAE.

```iecst
(* On/off hysteresis timer.
   Signal must stay TRUE for tActivate before Q goes TRUE.
   Signal must stay FALSE for tDeactivate before Q goes FALSE. *)
FUNCTION_BLOCK FB_EMS_HysteresisTimer
```

For simple FBs, a single line is enough:

```iecst
(* Floating average over 1 minute sample window. *)
FUNCTION_BLOCK FB_EMS_FloatingAvg_1m
```

## VAR_INPUT / VAR_OUTPUT — Always Commented

Every input and output **must** have an inline `(* *)` comment. Format: `(* [unit] Purpose *)`

```iecst
VAR_INPUT
    bEnable       : BOOL;  (* Enable the controller *)
    rW            : REAL;  (* Setpoint value *)
    rX            : REAL;  (* Actual value (process variable) *)
    rDeadRange    : REAL;  (* [%] Dead band relative to output range *)
    rKp           : REAL;  (* Proportional gain *)
    tTi           : TIME;  (* Integration time *)
    rYMin         : REAL;  (* [A] Minimum output value *)
    rYMax         : REAL;  (* [A] Maximum output value *)
END_VAR
VAR_OUTPUT
    rY        : REAL;  (* Controller output *)
    bMaxLimit : BOOL;  (* TRUE when output hit upper limit *)
    bMinLimit : BOOL;  (* TRUE when output hit lower limit *)
    bError    : BOOL;  (* Error flag *)
END_VAR
```

Rules:
- Physical units in brackets at the start: `(* [A] *)`, `(* [W] *)`, `(* [kWh] *)`, `(* [%] *)`, `(* [ms] *)`
- BOOL: describe TRUE condition: `(* TRUE when charging is active *)`
- Keep it short — one line, no period at end
- English comments

## VAR Section Headers

Group private variables with `(* section name *)` headers:

```iecst
VAR
    (* edge triggers *)
    _posEdgePlugged : R_TRIG;
    _negEdgeDone    : F_TRIG;

    (* timers *)
    _fbTonTest      : TON;
    _fbTonFailsafe  : TON;

    (* state *)
    _nStep   : INT;
    _bActive : BOOL;
END_VAR
```

One blank line between sections. No `(* *)` header needed for small VAR blocks (< 5 vars).

## Code Block Separators

Use `(* --- Purpose --- *)` to separate logical sections in implementation code:

```iecst
(* --- Rising edge of enable signal --- *)
_posEdgeEnable(CLK := bEnable);

(* --- Parameter validation --- *)
IF rKp <= 0 THEN
    bError := TRUE;
    RETURN;
END_IF

(* --- Calculate output --- *)
fY_P := fKp * fE;
```

Rules:
- At least 3 dashes on each side: `(* --- text --- *)`
- Lowercase text, short (3-6 words)
- One blank line before the separator, none after
- Use for logical groupings of 3+ related lines
- Do NOT use for single statements

## CASE Step Comments

In state machines (`CASE _nStep OF`), every case label gets an inline `(* purpose *)` comment on the same line:

```iecst
CASE _nStep OF
    0: (* idle — wait for enable *)
        IF bEnable THEN
            _nStep := 1;
        END_IF

    1: (* start initialization *)
        _bBusy := TRUE;
        _nStep := 2;

    9: (* barrier — all views must have completed phase 2 *)
        IF _stClientState.nRrViewInit2 >= _stClientState.nViewCount THEN
            _stClientState.eViewInitStatus := E_EB_BA_ViewInitStatus.Done;
            _nStep := 10;
        END_IF

    10: (* mark this view as fully initialized *)
        _bDone := TRUE;
END_CASE
```

Rules:
- Comment format: `(* short purpose *)` — directly after the case label on the same line
- Do not repeat the step number in the comment — the case label already shows it
- Keep it short (3-10 words), describe the intent, not the code
- Every case label must have a step comment — no exceptions
- One blank line between case blocks for readability

## Action / Method Headers (optional, for large FBs only)

For complex actions/methods in large FBs, use a 3-line block header:

```iecst
(* ------------------------------------------- *)
(*               Initial Sync                  *)
(* ------------------------------------------- *)
```

Only use this for FBs with 5+ actions/methods. Small FBs don't need it.

## What NOT to Comment

- Do not narrate obvious code: `(* Set bDone to TRUE *)` on `bDone := TRUE;`
- Do not comment END_IF / END_CASE / END_FOR
- Do not duplicate the variable name: `bEnable : BOOL; (* Enable flag for bEnable *)`
- Do not write TODO/FIXME without a name and date
- Do not use `//` comments — always use `(* *)` syntax
- Internal VAR members: comments optional (only if purpose is non-obvious)

## STRUCT Members

Same rules as VAR_INPUT — each member gets an inline comment:

```iecst
TYPE ST_EMS_ECabinet_Param :
    STRUCT
        fMaxCurrent         : REAL := 120;  (* [A] Max current per phase *)
        fMaxFailsafeCurrent : REAL := 72;   (* [A] Failsafe current limit *)
        bCalculateCircuits  : BOOL := TRUE; (* TRUE: dynamic distribution *)
    END_STRUCT
END_TYPE
```
